INSERT INTO `fn_posts` VALUES (1718, 1, '2015-03-23 05:06:09', '2015-03-23 05:06:09', '<h2>Objective</h2>\r\nTo create a pixel-perfect recreation of an existing site without looking at the code, and using only HTML and CSS.\r\n<h2>Implementation</h2>\r\nI chose the Lungren+Lindqvist site because I was interested in minimal Swiss-style design being used on the Web. The challenge of getting the spacing and elements right was exciting.\r\n\r\nI roughed-out the 4-column layout first, as it''s repeated throughout the site. Then it was a lot of trial and error getting the heights and spacing right on the different elements. I captured all the images using screenshots, but I couldn''t figure out the screen-effect overlay when you hover over the images.\r\n\r\nI settled on using CSS image sprites for all the images on the site, getting the total number of images down to 5, and learning a lot about image sprites along the way.\r\n<h2>What I''d do differently now</h2>\r\nI was really proud of the image sprites at the time (still am, in a way), but I know now that they aren''t semantic, so I''d need to come up with a better solution for the overlay effect.\r\n\r\nThere''s also more paring-down I could do in both the HTML and CSS. There are several instances of redundant CSS, like this code to eliminate the margin on columns on the right edge:\r\n<pre><code>.column2{ width:460px; margin:0 20px 0 0; float:left; overflow:hidden; } .column2-right{ width:460px; margin:0; float:left; overflow:hidden; } </code></pre>\r\nClearing out the redundancies will make the code cleaner and reduce the file size, making it faster overall and easier to update down the road.', 'Pixel Perfect: Recreating an existing site', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'pixel-perfect-recreating-an-existing-site', '', '', '2015-03-23 20:32:10', '2015-03-23 20:32:10', '', 0, 'http://www.frank-nelson.com//?post_type=project&#038;p=1718', 0, 'project', '', 0);
