INSERT INTO `fn_posts` VALUES (1722, 1, '2015-03-23 20:16:29', '2015-03-23 20:16:29', '<h2>Objective</h2>\r\nI wanted to see if I could build a javascript function that would randomly generate an RGBA value that I could then assign to different elements in the DOM.\r\n<h2>Implementation</h2>\r\nI figured out that I needed to assign each RGB a random number between 0-255 and then concatenate them so it could be pushed into the CSS:\r\n<pre><code>var app = {  colorMachine: function() { var R = getRandomInt(0, 255); var G = getRandomInt(0, 255); var B = getRandomInt(0, 255); var randomColor = (R + "," + G + "," + B + "," + 1); var newColor = "rgba(" + randomColor + ")"; return newColor; }, </code></pre>\r\nThen I used jQuery to assign the five background columns the color values, and set them to change at a random interval between 0.5 and 2 seconds:\r\n<pre><code>timeMachine:function(){ var T = getRandomInt(5, 20); var newT = (T+"00"); return newT; },  pageStyles: function(){ $("div #1 h1").html(app.colorMachine()); $("div #1").css({ ''background-color'': app.colorMachine() }); </code></pre>\r\n<h2>Next steps</h2>\r\nIt works pretty well now, but I want to make it more modular. Right now it needs to hook into div #ID''s to work, but I''d like to get it to the point where you could choose the number of columns and the code would automatically create them.', 'Javascript random color experiment', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'javascript-random-color-experiment', '', '', '2015-03-23 21:46:40', '2015-03-23 21:46:40', '', 0, 'http://www.frank-nelson.com//?post_type=project&#038;p=1722', 0, 'project', '', 0);
