INSERT INTO `fn_posts` VALUES (1738, 1, '2015-03-23 20:20:15', '2015-03-23 20:20:15', '<h2>Objective</h2>\r\nTo build a plug-in tool with javascript that could be used on a site we were working on. Since I was working on a responsive site, I chose to build a tool to create a pop-up window the size of a different device so you could see how the layout looked at that size.\r\n<h2>Implementation</h2>\r\nI used <a href="http://fortawesome.github.io/Font-Awesome/icons/" target="_blank">FontAwesome icons</a> to represent the device sizes, and jQuery to create the hide/show effect on the menu.\r\n\r\nIt took a lot of trial and error to come to get the device withs and sizes working properly, but the code itself is pretty simple:\r\n<pre><code>openNewWindow: function(){ //new window features, size, options...etc //35px added to width to accomodate scroll bar and outer border of window var newPop; var currentURL= window.location.href; var maxW = screen.width; var maxH = screen.height; var newWinSpecs = "scrollbars=yes,status=yes,height=1,width=1";  $(''#desktop'').click (function(){ if(window.isPopup===undefined){ console.log("you just clicked on the desktop!"); newPop = window.open(currentURL, "", newWinSpecs); newPop.resizeTo(maxW, maxH); newPop.isPopup = true; } else{ window.resizeTo(maxW, maxH); } }); </code></pre>\r\nIt was really satisfying when the I got the tool to work properly. Javascript was really challenging to learn bacause I had been so used to how concrete HTML and CSS are as languages. The abstract nature of javascript was hard to adjust to, but I recognize how much power it has. I''m looking forward to learning more.', 'Javascript plug-in for testing responsive designs', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'javascript-plug-in-for-testing-responsive-designs', '', '', '2015-03-23 21:45:33', '2015-03-23 21:45:33', '', 0, 'http://www.frank-nelson.com//?post_type=project&#038;p=1738', 0, 'project', '', 0);
