INSERT INTO `fn_posts` VALUES (1740, 1, '2015-03-23 20:24:14', '2015-03-23 20:24:14', '<h2>Objective</h2>\r\nUsing an existing responsive grid system, build a four-page responsive site dedicated to a public service, with each page having a different layout.\r\n<h2>Implementation</h2>\r\nI chose <a href="http://www.getskeleton.com/" target="_blank">Skeleton</a> as my grid system. Skeleton uses up to 16 columns, but I used 12. This allowed me to use 6, 4, and 3-column layouts to differentiate each page.\r\n\r\nThe header, footer, nav and image/video clear all the columns on each page, creating consistency in the layout while the number of column change. The footer and nav are set to cover the full width of the browser window. This makes the layout feel like it''s part of the larger viewing area, even though it''s centered horizontally.\r\n\r\nI used a couple different methods to accomplish the responsive aspect of the design, but primarily I used the<code>float:left</code> style and then manipulated the widths of the columns so they would sit next to each other and then stack on top of each other as the viewing portal gets smaller:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.frank-nelson.com//wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign2_3.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-1741" src="http://www.frank-nelson.com//wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign2_3-300x154.png" alt="webdesign2_3" width="300" height="154" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.frank-nelson.com//wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign2_4.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-1742" src="http://www.frank-nelson.com//wp-content/uploads/2015/03/webdesign2_4-191x300.png" alt="webdesign2_4" width="191" height="300" /></a>', 'Responsive informational site', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'responsive-informational-site', '', '', '2015-03-23 21:45:07', '2015-03-23 21:45:07', '', 0, 'http://www.frank-nelson.com//?post_type=project&#038;p=1740', 0, 'project', '', 0);
